title: phylotypr
text: classify sequence need DNA sequence character object like unknown . unknown object can classified using classify_sequence() along database object (.e., db). output classify_sequence list taxonomic levels kingdom (domain) genus confidence scores sequence taxonomic levels example, ’ll notice family genus assignment confidence scores 80%. value commonly used mothur used RDP website. filter classification level confidence, can use filter_taxonomy() function: see “Porphyromonadaceae” “Barnesiella” names removed along confidence score. convert list format string, can use print_taxonomy() function:
code: unknown <- "TACGGAGGATGCGAGCGTTATCCGGATTTATTGGGTTTAAAGGGTGCGTAGGCGGATCGTTAAGTCAGTGGTCAAATTGAGGGGCTCAACCCCTTCCCGCCATTGAAACTGGCGATCTTGAGTGGAAGAGAAGTATGCGGAATGCGTGGTGTAGCGGTGAAATGCATAGATATCACGCAGAACCCCGATTGCGAAGGCAGCATGCCGGCTTCCTACTGACGCTCATGCACGAAAGTGTGGGTAACGAACAGG" consensus <- classify_sequence(unknown = unknown, database = db) consensus #> $taxonomy #> [1] "Bacteria"           "Bacteroidetes"      "Bacteroidia"        #> [4] "Bacteroidales"      "Porphyromonadaceae" "Barnesiella"        #>  #> $confidence #> [1] 100  95  83  83  79  56 filtered <- filter_taxonomy(consensus) filtered #> $taxonomy #> [1] "Bacteria"      "Bacteroidetes" "Bacteroidia"   "Bacteroidales" #>  #> $confidence #> [1] 100  95  83  83 print_taxonomy(filtered) #> [1] "Bacteria(100);Bacteroidetes(95);Bacteroidia(83);Bacteroidales(83);Bacteroidales_unclassified(83);Bacteroidales_unclassified(83)"

title: phylotypr
text: likely multiple sequences like classify. phylotypr package installs example FASTA-formatted file, “miseq_sop.fasta”. code shows can read FASTA-formatted file classify sequences. , show can use map_chr() function purrr, something like . Note classifying data replace phylotypr_example(...) path data.

what: Classifying multiple unknown sequences in parallel
title: phylotypr
text: furrr package allows run classify_sequence() parallel. , computer 8 processors, furrr split data 4 chunks classify chunk separately pulling together. can alter number processors changing value assigned workers argument plan(). testing, found increasing number processors provides diminishing returns. example, 4 10 processors took amount time execute. value future.globals.maxSize may need increased database gets larger. Finally, classify_sequence() uses random number generator create bootstrap replicates, need provide seed future_map_chr(). ’ll notice furrr_options() argument. Feel free adjust desired seed.
code: library(dplyr) library(furrr)  miseq <- read_fasta(phylotypr_example("miseq_sop.fasta.gz"))  plan(strategy = multisession, workers = 4) options(future.globals.maxSize = 10000000000)  miseq |>   mutate(     classification = future_map_chr(       sequence,       ~ classify_sequence(unknown = .x, database = db) |>         filter_taxonomy() |>         print_taxonomy(),       .progress = TRUE,       .options = furrr_options(seed = 19760620)     )   )

title: phylotypr
text: Consider results classifying unknown three times: ’ll notice classification three replicates varies slightly. , due use random number generator getting confidence scores bounce around 80%, results different levels filtering. get stable classification, setting random number generator seed set.seed(). get precise confidence score, set num_bootstraps = 1000 classify_sequence(). forewarned function take 10-times longer run 10-times number bootstraps!
code: map_chr(   rep(unknown, 3),   ~ classify_sequence(unknown = .x, database = db, num_bootstraps = 100) |>     filter_taxonomy() |>     print_taxonomy() ) #> [1] "Bacteria(100);Bacteroidetes(97);Bacteroidia(83);Bacteroidales(83);Porphyromonadaceae(81);Porphyromonadaceae_unclassified(81)" #> [2] "Bacteria(100);Bacteroidetes(98);Bacteroidia(86);Bacteroidales(86);Porphyromonadaceae(85);Porphyromonadaceae_unclassified(85)" #> [3] "Bacteria(100);Bacteroidetes(96);Bacteroidia(86);Bacteroidales(86);Porphyromonadaceae(85);Porphyromonadaceae_unclassified(85)" map_chr(   rep(unknown, 3),   ~ classify_sequence(unknown = .x, database = db, num_bootstraps = 100) |>     filter_taxonomy() |>     print_taxonomy() ) #> [1] "Bacteria(99);Bacteroidetes(94);Bacteroidetes_unclassified(94);Bacteroidetes_unclassified(94);Bacteroidetes_unclassified(94);Bacteroidetes_unclassified(94)"  #> [2] "Bacteria(100);Bacteroidetes(100);Bacteroidia(93);Bacteroidales(93);Porphyromonadaceae(88);Porphyromonadaceae_unclassified(88)"                               #> [3] "Bacteria(100);Bacteroidetes(95);Bacteroidetes_unclassified(95);Bacteroidetes_unclassified(95);Bacteroidetes_unclassified(95);Bacteroidetes_unclassified(95)"

Classify 16S rRNA gene sequence fragment — classify_sequence
text: unknown_sequence character object representing DNA sequence needs classified database kmer database generated using build_kmer_database kmer_size integer value (default 8) indicating size kmers use classifying sequences. Higher values use RAM potentially specificity Lower values use less RAM potentially less specificity. Benchmarking found default 8 provides best specificity lowest possible memory requirement fastest execution time. num_bootstraps integer value (default 100). value num_bootstraps number randomizations perform 1/kmer_size kmers sampled (without replacement) unknown_sequence.
